Lagos – Nigerian equities market continued its downward movement yesterday with investors losing N63 billion just as the two major indicators went down by 0.43 per cent each.
The All Share Index shed 175.78 absolute points, representing a decline of 0.43 per cent to close at 40,249.29 points, while market capitalisation declined by N63 billion to close at N14.580 trillion.
The downturn was impacted by losses recorded in medium and large capitalised stocks, amongst which are; Mobil Nigeria, Dangote Cement, Nigerian Breweries, Dangote Sugar and Flour Mills of Nigeria.
Analysts at Afrinvest Limited said: “despite yesterday’s negative performance, we anticipate a rebound in the near term. We expect investors to react positively to the first quarter, 2018 GDP released as well as existing cheap valuations in the market.”
Market breadth closed negative, with 19 gainers versus 34 losers. Ikeja Hotel recorded the highest price gain of 9.68 per cent, to close at N2.04 per share. Cement Company of Northern Nigeria gained five per cent to close at N25.20, while Okomu Oil appreciated by 4.97 per cent to close at N82.30 per share.
AIICO Insurance appreciated by 4.84 per cent to close at 65 kobo, while First Aluminium gained 4.76 per cent to close at 44 kobo per share. On the other hand, Eterna Oil led the losers’ chart by 8.55 per cent, to close at N6.20, while Honeywell Flour and The Initiates followed with a decline of five each to close at N2.47 and 76 kobo per share respectively.
LASACO Assurance shed 4.88 per cent to close at 39 kobo, while African Alliance Insurance depreciated by 4.76 per cent to close at 20 kobo per share.
However, the total volume traded rose by 3.68 per cent to 281.26 million shares, worth N4.1 billion, and traded in 4,304 deals. Transactions in the shares of Ikeja Hotel topped the activity chart with 34.55 million shares valued at N70.49 million. Fidson Healthcare followed with 32.43 million shares worth N180.2 million, while Zenith Bank traded 26.46 million shares valued at N740.88 million.
